{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"65279a09-04ea-42a1-a1ca-0078f1e88498","content":"## Analysis\n\nThe project and report confirm the issue: **MSBuild process startup and project re-evaluation** on every `dotnet build` invocation is the bottleneck — not compilation itself. Visual Studio avoids this by keeping a long-lived MSBuild server process.\n\nHere are the recommended fixes, from highest to lowest impact:\n\n### 1. Enable the MSBuild Build Server (biggest win)\n\n.NET 8 SDK includes an opt-in MSBuild server that keeps the process warm between builds — just like VS does:\n\n```bash\nexport DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1\ndotnet build              # first build: normal speed\ndotnet build              # subsequent: much faster (warm server)\n```\n\nAdd to your shell profile (`.bashrc`/`.zshrc`) to make it permanent. On .NET 9+ this becomes the default.\n\n### 2. Use `dotnet watch` for the inner loop\n\nFor edit-build-test cycles, keep a watcher running instead of invoking `dotnet build` manually:\n\n```bash\ndotnet watch build        # rebuilds on file changes\ndotnet watch run          # rebuilds + re-runs\n```\n\nThis eliminates startup overhead entirely since the host process stays alive.\n\n### 3. Use the terminal logger to reduce I/O overhead\n\n```bash\ndotnet build --tl\n```\n\nThe terminal logger (`--tl`) uses a more efficient output mode that reduces console I/O during builds.\n\n---\n\n**Summary**: The root cause is that `dotnet build` pays a cold-start tax on every invocation. The MSBuild server (`DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1`) is the direct fix — it gives CLI builds the same warm-process advantage Visual Studio has. Pair it with `dotnet watch` for the fastest inner loop.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"94915dad-7df1-4a79-9310-5e551f43d82a","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Now I understand the issue. The developer is experiencing slow CLI builds with `dotnet build` even for incremental/no-op builds. The overhead is from MSBuild process startup and project graph re-evaluation on every CLI invocation.\n\nThe key insight here is:\n\n1. **Visual Studio** keeps MSBuild running as a long-lived process (the build server), so project evaluation and JIT warmup only happen once. Subsequent builds reuse the warm process.\n\n2. **`dotnet build`** by default starts a new MSBuild process each time (or at least re-evaluates), which causes 2-4 seconds of overhead even for no-op builds.\n   \nThe main solution is to enable the MSBuild build server in .NET 8+, which keeps the MSBuild process alive between invocations just like Visual Studio does. I can enable this either through the `DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1` environment variable or by using the `--tl` flag with `dotnet build`.\n\nFor iterative development, `dotnet watch` is the better approach since it maintains a long-running process with file watchers that automatically trigger rebuilds when code changes.\n\nI should also clarify the MSBuild server situation—in .NET 8 it requires the `DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1` environment variable, but .NET 9 enables it by default. For multi-project solutions, `dotnet build --graph` can optimize the build order and parallelization.","outputTokens":1247},"id":"294b4d41-4af2-4cff-9d3d-99fd6ae59d81","timestamp":"2026-04-03T00:50:02.207Z","parentId":"95399f5e-9ce6-45df-8fc5-b64d7d24a7b3"}
